<node CREATED="1379263792190" ID="ID_1907024027" MODIFIED="1379263808181" TEXT="The implementation approach of converting all arguments to inexact numbers if any argument is inexact is not transitive. "/>
<node CREATED="1379263808183" ID="ID_10823863" MODIFIED="1379263879898">
<richcontent TYPE="NODE"><html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      For example, let <font face="Courier">big</font>&#xa0;be <font face="Courier">(expt 2 1000)</font>, and assume that <font face="Courier">big</font>&#xa0; is exact and that inexact numbers are represented by 64-bit IEEE binary floating point numbers.&#xa0;
    </p>
  </body>
</html></richcontent>
</node>
<node CREATED="1379263813743" ID="ID_1612173504" MODIFIED="1379263917309">
<richcontent TYPE="NODE"><html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      Then <font face="Courier">(= (- big 1) (inexact big))</font>&#xa0;and <font face="Courier">(= (inexact big) (+ big 1))</font>&#xa0;would both be true with this approach, because of the limitations of IEEE representations of large integers, whereas <font face="Courier">(= (- big 1) (+ big 1))</font>&#xa0;is false.&#xa0;
    </p>
  </body>
</html></richcontent>
</node>
<node CREATED="1379263821152" ID="ID_852843889" MODIFIED="1379263944185">
<richcontent TYPE="NODE"><html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      Converting inexact values to exact numbers that are the same (in the sense of <font face="Courier">=</font>) to them will avoid this problem, though special care must be taken with infinities.
    </p>
  </body>
</html></richcontent>
