<node CREATED="1377922036392" ID="ID_687915872" MODIFIED="1378688399131">
<richcontent TYPE="NODE"><html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      Within literal expressions and representations of objects read by the <font face="Courier">read</font>&#xa0; procedure, the forms <font face="Courier">&#x2019;</font>&#x27e8;datum&#x27e9;, <font face="Courier">`</font>&#x27e8;datum&#x27e9;, <font face="Courier">,</font>&#x27e8;datum&#x27e9;, and <font face="Courier">,@</font>&#x27e8;datum&#x27e9; denote two-element lists whose first elements are the symbols <font face="Courier">quote</font>, <font face="Courier">quasiquote</font>, <font face="Courier">unquote</font>, and <font face="Courier">unquote-splicing</font>, respectively.
    </p>
  </body>
</html></richcontent>
</node>
<node CREATED="1378688399140" ID="ID_1875376960" MODIFIED="1378688404282">
<richcontent TYPE="NODE"><html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      The second element in each case is &#x27e8;datum&#x27e9;.
    </p>
  </body>
</html></richcontent>
</node>
<node CREATED="1378688404284" ID="ID_1961664827" MODIFIED="1378688408552">
<richcontent TYPE="NODE"><html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      This convention is supported so that arbitrary Scheme programs can be represented as lists.
    </p>
  </body>
</html></richcontent>
</node>
<node CREATED="1378688408554" ID="ID_503321108" LINK="#ID_1958389477" MODIFIED="1378688465868">
<richcontent TYPE="NODE"><html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      That is, according to Scheme&#x2019;s grammar, every &#x27e8;expression&#x27e9; is also a &#x27e8;datum&#x27e9; (see section 7.1.2).
    </p>
  </body>
</html></richcontent>
</node>
<node CREATED="1378688420051" ID="ID_759909711" MODIFIED="1378688420057">
<richcontent TYPE="NODE"><html>
  <head>
    
  </head>
  <body>
    <p>
      Among other things, this permits the use of the <font face="Courier">read</font>&#xa0;procedure to parse Scheme programs.
    </p>
  </body>
</html></richcontent>
</node>
